    <div class="stack-row"><span class="stack-addr">+0x40</span><span class="stack-label">type-specific (cont.)</span><span class="stack-value">Bandage string size for Mummy</span></div>
    <div class="stack-row"><span class="stack-addr">+0x48</span><span class="stack-label">padding</span><span class="stack-value">Alignment padding</span></div>
  </div>

  <div class="callout callout-info">
    <div class="callout-title">Ghost Type Sizes</div>
    <p><strong>Werewolf (type=1, obj size=0x60)</strong>: Has a full moon boolean at +0x30. <strong>Mummy (type=5, obj size=0x78)</strong>: Has a bandage string at +0x30 (16 bytes: pointer + size). <strong>Vampire (type=7, obj size=0x60)</strong>: Has a blood value at +0x30. Werewolf and Vampire share the same allocation size (0x60), which is key for the overlap exploit.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="callout callout-warn">
    <div class="callout-title">Full RELRO Complication</div>
    <p>With Full RELRO, all GOT entries are resolved at startup and marked read-only. We cannot overwrite GOT entries to redirect execution. Instead, we must hijack the C++ vtable pointer to redirect virtual function calls. The vtable itself must be in a writable memory region that we control &mdash; either on the heap or in a data section with known offsets.</p>
  </div>
</section>

